mainEntity.name: How long does it take to hike North Tripyramid?

acceptedAnswer.text: Most routes on North Tripyramid take 5-7 hours round trip. The most popular trail is 10.2 miles with Hard difficulty. Start early, especially on weekends when parking fills quickly.

mainEntity.name: Is North Tripyramid hard to hike?

acceptedAnswer.text: North Tripyramid is rated Hard. At 4,180 feet, expect challenging terrain above treeline with potential for rapid weather changes. Proper footwear and preparation are essential.

mainEntity.name: Do I need a permit to hike North Tripyramid?

acceptedAnswer.text: No hiking permit is required for North Tripyramid. However, parking fees may apply at trailheads (typically $3-5/day for WMNF or state parks). A WMNF parking pass covers most White Mountain trailheads.

mainEntity.name: What is the best trail to hike North Tripyramid?

acceptedAnswer.text: The most popular route is the North Slide Trail, offering Extremely steep rock slide scramble. Not for beginners..

mainEntity.name: When is the best time to hike North Tripyramid?

acceptedAnswer.text: The best hiking season for North Tripyramid is late May through October. Summer and fall offer the best conditions, though expect crowds on weekends. Winter hiking requires specialized gear and experience.

page_content.description:
At 4,180 feet, North Tripyramid ranks among New Hampshire's celebrated 4000-Footers—a collection of 48 peaks that challenge and inspire hikers throughout the Northeast. This hard summit offers a quintessential White Mountain experience.

Popular Routes

The most popular route, **North Slide Trail**, covers 10.2 miles and is rated Hard. Extremely steep rock slide scramble. Not for beginners.

Peak Bagging

**Extend Your Adventure:** Middle Tripyramid lies just 0.8 miles away, making it an excellent addition for ambitious hikers looking to bag multiple summits.

spring.title: Spring Conditions
spring.conditions: Muddy trails, snow above 3000ft until May
spring.tips: Trail closures for mud season (April-May). Check conditions before heading out.

summer.title: Summer Conditions
summer.tips: Start early to avoid afternoon storms and parking issues. Peak crowds on weekends.

fall.title: Fall Conditions
fall.conditions: Peak foliage late Sept, early snow possible in October
fall.tips: Peak foliage brings peak crowds. Weekday hikes recommended. Watch for ice above treeline in late October.

winter.title: Winter Conditions
winter.conditions: Full winter conditions, extreme cold and wind above treeline
winter.tips: Winter hiking requires specialized skills and gear. Never hike alone. Check avalanche conditions for steeper terrain.
